and harm to receive national and global attention. In Defining Sexual Misconduct, Stacey Hannem and Christopher Schneider trace contemporary shifts in power in relation to the increased recognition and censure of sexual misconduct and the ways in which the shifting social landscape is communicated in the coverage of sexual misconduct in media. Hannem and Schneider also examine the contemporary dynamics of public accusations and their relationship to more formal criminal justice processes, as well as the implications for the stigmatization of alleged abusers and public response to alleged victims. Since behaviours categorized as sexual misconduct may not all be defined as crimes, or punishable through legal means, social censure and cancel culture often stand as proxy forms of punishment, and the authors reflect on what the pursuit of justice might look like in this extra-legal context.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMass media and crimezNorth America. 0aMass media and criminal justicezNorth America. 0aMass media and sexzNorth America. 0aMeToo movementxPress coveragezNorth America. 0aMeToo movementzNorth AmericaxPublic opinion. 0aSex crimesxPress coveragezNorth America. 0aSex offendersxPress coveragezNorth America. 0aSex offenderszNorth AmericaxPublic opinion. 0aSexual harassmentxPress coveragezNorth America. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh  a#metoo.  a#timesup.  aAshley Judd.  aAziz Ansari.  aBill Clinton.  aBill Cosby.  aDonald Trump.  aFacebook.  aHarvey Weinstein.  aInstagram.  aJian Ghomeshi.  aLouis C.K.  aNew York Times.  aSexual misconduct.  aShe Said.  aTarana Burke.  aTwitter.  aWashington Post.  acancel culture.  acommunication theory.  adiscourse.  afeminism.  afeminist standpoint theory.  ahegemony.  aintersectiona